        "ATLAS OCIO ACEScg FULL-FLOAT PLATE WORKFLOW — sci-fi hangar (third version in this series)\n\nExtends atlas_camera_inpaint_layers_hangar_workflow.json (the 3-band clean-plate sequel) with a genuine float-safe source plate and DCC export verification:\n\n  1. OCIORead loads examples/images/OCIO/atlasSpaceHangar_32bit_AcesCG.exr directly (32-bit float, ACEScg scene-linear) and converts ACEScg -> sRGB - Display for the ComfyUI-side tensor used to solve the camera and populate the viewport preview — the SAME 'display proxy vs. real float plate' split every exporter here already assumes (see nuke_exporter.py's Read-node comment).\n  2. AtlasRegisterPlate registers that SAME EXR path (colorspace=ACEScg, bit_depth=32f, role=source) as the durable plate_ref — is_proxy is False because a real, non-blank plate_path was supplied.\n  3. AtlasAttachSourcePlate attaches it onto the solve immediately after the learned solve, so it rides through every downstream deep-copy (AtlasCleanPlateLayer x3 all copy.deepcopy(solve) and only touch projection_sources/proxy_geometry — source_plate is untouched, confirmed by reading nodes.py).\n  4. The SAME three clean-plate bands as the previous hangar workflow (bg/mid/fg, tuned relief_grid 384 + depth_edge_rel 1.5) chain on top of the plated solve — nothing about the plate changes the clean-plate mechanics, it is pure metadata carried alongside.\n  5. Bake a camera move in the viewport (🎥 Camera Path -> pick a preset -> Apply Preset -> ⏺ Bake Proxy Path) to populate the camera_path output, then AtlasExportCameraPathUSD writes a time-sampled animated camera .usda from it.\n  6. AtlasExportNuke reads solve.source_plate (via exporters/_plate.py's primary_plate_path/primary_plate_colorspace helpers) to point its Read node at the REAL EXR with colorspace=ACEScg instead of a browser JPEG/PNG proxy — this is the actual full-float verification: open the generated script and confirm the Read node's file/colorspace knobs.\n  7. The detached AtlasViewportControls Output Desk feeds output_profile into BOTH the viewport and AtlasExportNuke directly (a direct optional-input wire, not an attach node) — its defaults are already ACEScg-flavored (working_colorspace=ACEScg, output_colorspace='ACES - ACEScg').\n  8. AtlasExportReliefMesh derives the real hangar geometry (OBJ) and feeds its obj_path into AtlasExportNuke's relief_mesh_obj_path input (same wiring pattern as AtlasExportMayaReviewScene) — both the .py and .nk Nuke exports then live-project the recovered camera onto that REAL mesh via ReadGeo2, instead of the default flat 40x40m ground card. Confirmed live (Nuke 16.1v3): ReadGeo2 reads the OBJ fine but does NOT auto-apply its MTL's own texture reference — the live Project3D2 projection wired into ReadGeo2's own image input (same topology as the Card case) is what actually textures it, which is also why this stays a genuine camera projection rather than a static UV bake even though the mesh's own baked UVs would technically make the raw photo 'look right' too.\n\nPATH GOTCHA (same caveat as atlas_camera_vfx_ocio_output_workflow.json): the OCIORead source and AtlasRegisterPlate plate_path widgets are hardcoded to this machine's absolute path (C:\\Users\\miike\\Desktop\\AtlasCamera_Claude\\examples\\images\\OCIO\\atlasSpaceHangar_32bit_AcesCG.exr). Point both widgets at your own local copy of the EXR before running — OCIORead accepts any absolute path 'anywhere on disk' (its own tooltip), it does not need to live under ComfyUI/input.\n\nRequires the ComfyUI-OCIO custom node pack (OCIORead) — see atlas_camera_vfx_ocio_output_workflow.json's own note for install steps. Needs [neural] for the learned solve + depth model.\n\nVERIFIED LIVE 2026-07-07 (full pipeline, not just reasoned through):\n  - OCIORead loads the real 3840x2160 32-bit-float ACEScg EXR and converts to sRGB - Display; AtlasLearnedSolveFromImage solves cleanly on that preview.\n  - Exported atlas_hangar_ocio_solve.json's source_plate: image_path = the real .exr, colorspace = ACEScg, bit_depth = 32f, is_proxy = false, metadata.path_exists = true.\n  - Baked a camera path in the real browser UI (Camera Path -> Orbit Left preset -> Apply Preset -> Bake Proxy Path) and re-queued; AtlasExportCameraPathUSD's camera_path.usda came out correctly time-sampled: startTimeCode=0, endTimeCode=47, framesPerSecond=24 (48 keyframe samples, matching frame_count=48/fps=24), upAxis=Y, and the pose arcs from an off-angle start to the recovered camera's own straight-on pose at frame 47 — exactly the documented Orbit Left 'arrive at the current vantage' behavior.\n  - AtlasExportNuke's nuke_projection.py Read node points at the SAME real EXR path with colorspace='ACEScg' (not the ComfyUI-side sRGB-Display preview), and its StickyNote carries the full output_profile dict from the Output Desk (working_colorspace=ACEScg, output_colorspace='ACES - ACEScg') — confirming AtlasExportNuke's optional output_profile input attaches onto the solve before export, per nodes.py's _clone_solve_with_metadata call.\n  - Without a bake, AtlasExportCameraPathUSD correctly raises 'No camera path yet...' rather than silently no-op'ing or crashing — verified by running the graph once before baking."
      ]
